In Dial. 28-30 the writer touches upon the important part formerly played by the mother in the training of children, and with this decaying custom contrasts the existing conditions by which children were often handed over to nurses and worthless servants: 28. 5 nan in cella emptae nutricis, sed in gremia ac sinu matris educabatur ,· 29. 1 at nunc natus infans delegatur Graeculae alicui ancillae, cui adiungitur unus aut alter ex amnibus servis, plerumque iratissimus. With these passages compare the following, where the similarity of language as well as of thought is par- ticularly striking: Agr.4 mater Iulia Procilla suit, rarae castitatis. In breius sinn indulgentiaque educatus per amnem honestarum artium cultum pueritiam adulescentiamque transegit ,· Ger. 20 secu areamque mater uberibus alit, nec ancillis aut nutricibus delegantur. ’
